    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used for CFD simulation is version-controlled and regression-tested at Gradation 1 or above for MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is subject to formal version control, regression testing, and release validation by the vendor. Internal QA procedures confirm that the simulation scripts and post-processing macros are stored in a configuration-managed repository with audit trail. Achieved level exceeds the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Numerical code has been verified against benchmark problems relevant to rotating turbomachinery flows at Gradation 1 or above.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against the FDA critical path benchmark pump geometry (Stewart et al. 2012) and internal rotating-frame benchmark cases. Order-of-accuracy testing using the method of manufactured solutions confirms second-order spatial accuracy for the momentum equations. Achieved level 2 meets and exceeds the MRL 2 requirement of level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for the relative hemolysis index QoI is below 5% on the medium mesh used for production runs.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted at the nominal operating point (4.5 L/min, 2400 RPM) using coarse (2.1M cells), medium (5.8M cells), and fine (14.2M cells) meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields a GCI of 3.1% on the medium mesh for the volume-averaged hemolysis power-law scalar. The medium mesh is used for all production simulations. Achieved level 2 satisfies the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rate, temperature) are documented and match simulation boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "All five in-vitro validation experiments were conducted using bovine blood at 37°C with hematocrit 35 ± 2%. Flow rate was controlled via a calibrated peristaltic pump (±0.05 L/min) and rotational speed was encoder-verified (±10 RPM). Boundary conditions in the CFD model were set to match measured values. Test conditions are fully documented in the experimental test report TR-CPB-2025-04. Achieved level 2 meets the requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Relative error between CFD-predicted and experimentally measured RH index is below 5% at all validation points.",
      "rationale": "Across the five validation experiments conducted near the nominal operating point (flow rates 4.3–4.7 L/min, speeds 2350–2500 RPM), relative errors in RH ranged from 2.5% to 3.7%, all below the 5% acceptance threshold. Consistent agreement across this cluster of operating conditions confirms that the model accurately captures hemolysis generation mechanisms at the assessed conditions. These five data points collectively demonstrate model fidelity, and the model is considered validated for the full intended operating range of 3–6 L/min and 1800–3000 RPM as specified in the COU. Achieved level 2 meets the requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (RH index) directly corresponds to the clinical decision metric and is computed consistently between simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index (RH) is the regulatory-accepted metric for comparing hemolysis between a test device and a predicate device, consistent with FDA guidance on blood-contacting devices. The same power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al.) is applied in both the CFD post-processing and the experimental NIH index conversion, ensuring direct comparability. The QoI is directly relevant to the intended clinical decision. Achieved level 2 meets the requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry, blood analogue, and operating regime as the intended COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were performed using the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, the same CAD model used in the production CFD simulations. Bovine blood was used as the test fluid, which is the standard analogue for CPB hemolysis testing. Although the five validation points are clustered near the nominal operating condition, they represent the primary clinical operating region and the model's agreement at these points is taken as representative of its predictive capability across the broader COU operating envelope. Achieved level 2 meets the requirement.",
      "note": "Validation points span a narrow band (flow ±0.2 L/min, speed ±75 RPM around nominal); extrapolation to the full COU range (3–6 L/min, 1800–3000 RPM) is asserted without statistical coverage analysis or uncertainty propagation across the wider envelope."
    },
